By the Angle Bisector Theorem, $BD = \frac{ac}{a + c} = \frac{28}{11}$ and $DC = \frac{ab}{a + b} = \frac{36}{11},$ so
\[\overrightarrow{D} = \frac{a}{a + c} \overrightarrow{B} + \frac{c}{a + c} \overrightarrow{C} = \frac{3}{11} \overrightarrow{B} + \frac{8}{11} \overrightarrow{C}.\]Similarly,
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{E} &= \frac{b}{a + b} \overrightarrow{A} + \frac{a}{a + b} \overrightarrow{C} = \frac{4}{13} \overrightarrow{A} + \frac{9}{13} \overrightarrow{C}, \\
\overrightarrow{F} &= \frac{b}{a + b} \overrightarrow{A} + \frac{a}{a + b} \overrightarrow{B} = \frac{4}{11} \overrightarrow{A} + \frac{7}{11} \overrightarrow{B}.
\end{align*}Then
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{I} &= \frac{1}{3} (\overrightarrow{D} + \overrightarrow{E} + \overrightarrow{F}) \\
&= \frac{1}{3} \left( \frac{3}{11} \overrightarrow{B} + \frac{8}{11} \overrightarrow{C} + \frac{4}{13} \overrightarrow{A} + \frac{9}{13} \overrightarrow{C} + \frac{4}{11} \overrightarrow{A} + \frac{7}{11} \overrightarrow{B} \right) \\
&= \boxed{\left( \frac{4}{13}, \frac{10}{33}, \frac{17}{33} \right)}.
\end{align*}

